Data Visualisation - Road Casualties by Severity¶

The dataset is analysed to form insightful research questions and thus prepare the dataset accordingly. Following the pre-processing, a univariate analysis and visualisations have been done. Lastly, in light of research questions, multivariate analysis has been done. It has been observed that some geographical locations, time periods and demographic groups are more prone to casualties.

Following questions were asked throughout the project:

  • Are there specific locations prone to casualties?
  • Are there specific time periods prone to casualties?
  • Are there specific demographic groups prone to casualties?

Dataset was acquired through London Datastore website (https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset) under the name of Road Casualties by Severity, which is published by Department for Transport. The Road Casualties by Severity data (https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/road-casualties-severity-borough), was chosen, as it was published by a government office which makes the data trustworthy and valid. The data is collected through local authority incident records and aggregated by Department for Transport office.

Acquired dataset was a relatively tidy and clean dataset which I believe is due to the fact that data is coming from official records. In terms of tidying and pre-processing the data, following steps were taken:

  1. Column names are re-assigned for an easier coding purpose.
  2. The Pedestrian_locality column is dropped since it was containing inconsistent information with rest of the dataset. Even though the casualty class was categorized as pedestrian, Pedestrian_locality variable was categorized as not pedestrian which gives the impression that unknown locality is labelled as not pedestrian. In addition,more than 85% of the casualties labelled as not pedestrian. Therefore, it is concluded that analysing this variable will be misleading and thus, it is dropped.
  3. Rows containing incident records with unknown age variable is dropped in order univariate analysis to have consistency in itself. There were 681 casualty records with unknown age variable.
  4. No NA filling is done due to the fact that there were no missing values.
  5. Vehicle_type variable had 25 different categories such as: Motorcycle over 500cc, Motorcycle 50cc and under, etc. Since the project doesnt concern this amount of detail, for simplicity, categories aggregated into 11 such as: car, motorcycle, minibus, etc.
  6. Variable types are re-assigned in order to make accurate visualisations.

#Rename the columns in order to code easier
df.columns=['Easting','Northing','Severity_of_casualty','Casualty_class','Sex','Age','Date','Day_of_week',

#Drop the Pedestrian_locality column because of the inconsistency

df = df[(df.Age != 'unknown')]

#Setting data types
for i in df1.columns:
    if i=='Severity_of_casualty': #setting an ordinal variable
        Severity= ['Serious','Fatal']
        df1[i] = df1[i].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=Severity,ordered=True))
    elif i=='Day_of_week': #setting an ordinal variable
        Day=['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']
        df1[i] = df1[i].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=Day,ordered=True))
    elif i=='Age' or i=='Hour_of_day' or i=='Easting' or i=='Northing':
        df1[i] = df1[i].astype('int64')
    elif i=='Date':
        df1[i] = df1[i].astype('datetime64')
    else: #setting a nominal variable
        df1[i] = df1[i].astype('category')

The new Hour_of_day variable is an ordinal categorical variable with the mode of Evening Peak Hour and the median is same, Evening Peak Hour. A total of 3507 incidents were recorded during the evening peak hour which is between 16-19. This variable is categorized as follows:

  • 5 to 7 as Morning Before 7:30
  • 8 to 10 as Morning Peak Hour
  • 11 to 15 as Midday
  • 16 to 19 as Evening Peak Hour
  • 20 to 24 as Late Evening
  • 0 to 4 as Night

#Setting data types
for i in df3.columns:
    if i=='Severity_of_casualty': #setting an ordinal variable
        Severity= ['Serious','Fatal']
        df3[i] = df3[i].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=Severity,ordered=True))
    elif i=='Hour_of_day': #setting an ordinal variable
        Hour=['Morning - Before 7:30','Morning - Peak Hour', 'Midday', 'Evening - Peak Hour','Late Evening','Night']
        df3[i] = df3[i].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=Hour,ordered=True))
    elif i=='Day_of_week': #setting an ordinal variable
        Day=['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']
        df3[i] = df3[i].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=Day,ordered=True))
    elif i=='Age' or i=='Easting' or i=='Northing':
        df3[i] = df3[i].astype('int64')
    elif i=='Date':
        df3[i] = df3[i].astype('datetime64')
    else: #setting a nominal variable
        df3[i] = df3[i].astype('category')

#Setting data types
for i in ts.columns:
    if i=='Severity_of_casualty': #setting an ordinal variable
        Severity= ['Serious','Fatal']
        ts[i] = ts[i].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=Severity,ordered=True))
    elif i=='Day_of_week': #setting an ordinal variable
        Day=['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']
        ts[i] = ts[i].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=Day,ordered=True))
    elif i=='Age' or i=='Easting' or i=='Northing':
        ts[i] = ts[i].astype('int64')
    else: #setting a nominal variable
        ts[i] = ts[i].astype('category')

Results¶

There were three main research questions throughout the project. They can be listed as follows:

  • Are there specific locations prone to casualties?
  • Are there specific time periods prone to casualties?
  • Are there specific demographic groups prone to casualties?

Without a deeper study and analysis consisting multidisciplinary studies and multiple datasets, it will be wrong and misleading to give definite answers to these questions. However, the insight gained from the dataset cannot be overseen.

Through univariate analysis, it is observed that with 55.7% of frequency, drivers are more likely to involve in casualties. In addition, male frequency in casualties was significantly higher than female frequency with the percentage of 69.9%. Further, it is recognized that young people regardless of their sex are getting involved in casualties more than older people. However, it is noted that older women as pedestrians are more likely to get affected by casualties. These factors can be considered as demographics of people involved in casualties and may encourage the audience at issue to take some precautions and be more careful.

In addition to demographic groups, it is noticed that more populated locations such as inner boroughs (e.g. Westminster, Lambeth, etc.) have the highest frequencies of casualties. This finding can promote the need of precautions to be taken in specific locations (e.g. crowded streets, dangerous junctions, etc.).

Moreover, in terms of time, it is detected that highest number of casualties take place at 17:00, 18:00 and 08:00 which are basically corresponding to peak hours. One of the most accidents took place on Friday peak hours which is an indicator of people on the roads should be more careful regardless of other factors. In addition, it is noted that casualties at weekends happen mostly between 20:00-04:00 which can also be considered as something to keep in mind for the people go out on weekend nights.

In conclusion, this dataset was really good at pointing some indicators of casualties. However, further work can be done by using street level but not just local authorities in order to detect problematic locations and promote the need of precautions to be taken.
